{{Culture of Germany}}
As of 2018, ten firms in [[Germany]] rank among the world's biggest [[book publisher|publishers]] of [[books]] in terms of revenue: [[C.H. Beck]], [[Bertelsmann]], {{illm|Cornelsen Verlag|de}}, {{illm|Haufe-Gruppe|de}}, [[Holtzbrinck Publishing Group]], {{illm|Ernst Klett Verlag|de}}, [[Springer Nature]], [[Thieme Medical Publishers|Thieme]], {{illm|WEKA Holding|de}}, and [[Westermann Druck- und Verlagsgruppe]].<ref>{{citation |url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/print/20180917/78036-pearson-is-still-the-world-s-largest-publisher.html |title= The World's 54 Largest Publishers, 2018 |date= 14 September 2018 |work=[[Publishers Weekly]] |location=US |volume=265 |number= 38 }}</ref>{{refn|group=nb|Of these, several also topped the list in 2016 and 2017.<ref>{{citation |work=Publishers Weekly |location=US |url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/international/international-book-news/article/71268-the-world-s-52-largest-book-publishers-2016.html |title=World's 52 Largest Book Publishers, 2016 |date= 26 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{citation |work=[[Publishers Weekly]] |location=US |url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/international/international-book-news/article/74505-the-world-s-50-largest-publishers-2017.html |title=World's 54 Largest Publishers, 2017 |date= 25 August 2017}}</ref>}} Overall, "Germany has some 2,000 publishing houses, and more than 90,000 titles reach the public each year, a production surpassed only by the [[Books in the United States|United States]]."<ref name=Britannica>{{cite web |work=[[Britannica.com]] |url= https://www.britannica.com/place/Germany/Cultural-institutions |title=Germany: Media and Publishing |accessdate= 26 November 2017 }}</ref> Unlike many other countries, "book publishing is not centered in a single city but is concentrated fairly evenly in [[Berlin]], [[Hamburg]], and the regional metropolises of [[Cologne]], [[Frankfurt]], [[Stuttgart]], and [[Munich]]."<ref name=Britannica />

==History==
{{see also|Global spread of the printing press#Germany}}

In the 1450s in [[Mainz]], [[Johannes Gutenberg]] printed a ''[[Gutenberg Bible|Bible]]'' using [[movable type|movable metal type]], a technique that quickly spread to other German towns and throughout Europe.{{sfn|Proctor|1898}}

In the 1930s [[Nazis]] conducted [[Nazi book burnings|book burnings]].

German publishers issued around 61,000 book titles in 1990, and around 83,000 in 2000.{{sfn|Euromedia|2004}}

==Fairs==
The influential [[Frankfurt Book Fair]] began in 1454, and the  [[Leipzig Book Fair]] in 1632.

==Collections==
{{see also|List of libraries in Germany}}

Outside of Germany, collections of German books include those stored in the UK at the [[British Library]]<ref>{{cite web |publisher=British Library |location=UK |work= Help for Researchers |url= http://www.bl.uk/reshelp/findhelprestype/prbooks/index.html |title= German Printed Collections, 1501-1850 |accessdate=8 December 2017 }}</ref> and [[London Library]];<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.londonlibrary.co.uk/images/PDFs/GermanColl.pdf |publisher=London Library |location=UK |title=Guide to German Collections |accessdate= 8 December 2017}} (Describes German-language holdings)</ref> in the US at [[Harvard University]]<ref>{{cite journal |title=Twenty Years of German Collection Building, 1966-1986 |author= James Walsh |journal= Harvard Library Bulletin |location=US |issn=0017-8136 |volume=33 |url= https://iiif.lib.harvard.edu/manifests/view/drs:427334919$91i |year=1985 }} + {{cite journal |title=Exhibition of German Illustrated Books from the Sixteenth Century |author= Roger Wieck |journal= Harvard Library Bulletin |volume=29 |url= https://iiif.lib.harvard.edu/manifests/view/drs:427334885$102i |year=1981 }} {{free access}}</ref> and [[Yale University]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://beinecke.library.yale.edu/collections/curatorial-areas/german-literature |title=Collections: German Literature |publisher=Yale University Library |location=US |accessdate= 8 December 2017}}</ref>

==In popular culture==
In 2006 a temporary sculpture about German book history was installed at [[Bebelplatz]] in Berlin as part of the [[Walk of Ideas]].

