{{Infobox ancient site |name = Jebel Aabeby |native_name = |alternate_name = |image = |alt = |caption = |map_type = Lebanon |map_alt = |map_size = |location = {{convert|2|km|mi}} southeast of [[Sidon]], [[Lebanon]] |region = |coordinates = {{coord|33.5525|35.396389|display=inline}} |type = terraces |part_of = |length = |width = |area = |height = |builder = |material = |built = |abandoned = |epochs = [[Heavy Neolithic]], [[Neolithic]] |cultures = [[Qaraoun culture]] |dependency_of = |occupants = |event = |excavations = 1965 |archaeologists = [[Henri Fleisch]], V. Hankey and [[Lorraine Copeland]] |condition = under cultivation |ownership = |management = |public_access = Yes |website = |notes = }} '''Jebel Aabeby''' is an archaeological site approximately {{convert|2|km|mi}} southeast of [[Sidon]], to the west of the road north to [[Qraye]] in [[Lebanon]].<ref name="CopelandWescombe1965">{{cite book|author1=Lorraine Copeland|author2=P. Wescombe|title=Inventory of Stone-Age sites in Lebanon, p. 93|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6YsRRwAACAAJ|accessdate=21 July 2011|year=1965|publisher=Imprimerie Catholique}}</ref><ref name="Hours1994">{{cite book|author=Francis Hours|title=Atlas des sites du proche orient (14000-5700 BP)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KlZtAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=5 September 2012|year=1994|publisher=Maison de l'Orient méditerranéen|isbn=978-2-903264-53-6}}</ref> The site is on a hill where a number of [[Cedar of Lebanon|Cedar]] trees surround the Mar Elias monastery on the western side of the summit. A [[Heavy Neolithic]] assemblage of [[flint]] tools made by the [[Qaraoun culture]] was collected from some [[Olive]] terraces bordering on the road and from an area above them that was disturbed in the construction of a trackway. The flint was of a brown, [[Nummulitic]], [[Eocene]] type, some having been [[patinated]] to white while others were found fresh. Several broad blades were found along with heavy scrapers on flakes, massive cores, [[Plane (tool)|rabot]]s, [[racloir]]s and a few smaller scrapers. The material now stored in the [[Museum of Lebanese Prehistory]] was studied by [[Henri Fleisch]], who concluded that the site was likely used as a [[prehistoric]] [[factory]].<ref name="CopelandWescombe1965"/>
